    rationale: "The surgical timeout (part of The Joint Commission's Universal Protocol) requires verification of: (1) Correct patient identity (using two identifiers), (2) Correct procedure (matching the consent form), (3) Correct surgical site (confirming site marking), (4) Availability of correct implants and special equipment, (5) Antibiotic prophylaxis administration (within 1 hour of incision for most antibiotics, 2 hours for vancomycin). Additional items commonly verified during timeout include: patient allergies, venous thromboembolism prophylaxis, anticipated blood loss, availability of blood products, fire risk assessment, and imaging display. ALL team members must actively participate in the timeout — the procedure must not begin until all elements are confirmed.",
    difficulty: 2,
