    rationale: "The Padgett dermatome is an electric or air-powered instrument that harvests split-thickness skin grafts (STSGs) of uniform width and thickness. The surgeon adjusts the dermatome blade width and thickness settings (typically 0.012-0.015 inches for most STSGs). The donor site (commonly the thigh) is lubricated with mineral oil, and the dermatome is guided smoothly across the skin to harvest the graft. The surgical technologist must ensure the dermatome blade is properly seated, the guard is correctly positioned, and the power source is functional. Alternatively, the Zimmer air-powered dermatome or Humby knife (manual) may be used. The harvested graft may be passed through a mesh device to create a meshed graft that can expand to cover a larger area.",
