    id: "st-1541",
    stem: "The surgeon is performing a sentinel lymph node biopsy during a breast cancer procedure. The surgical technologist should anticipate the need for:",
    options: ["A specimen container without formalin for fresh frozen section analysis and a gamma detection probe for radiotracer localization", "Multiple containers of formalin for the anticipated large number of lymph node specimens", "A tourniquet applied to the affected arm to enhance lymphatic visualization", "Electrosurgery at maximum settings to identify the sentinel node by tissue response"],
    correctIndex: 0,
    rationale: "Sentinel lymph node biopsy (SLNB) identifies the first lymph node(s) receiving drainage from the tumor site. The technique uses either a radioactive tracer (Technetium-99m sulfur colloid injected preoperatively) detected with a gamma probe, isosulfan blue dye (Lymphazurin) or indocyanine green (ICG), or a combination. The surgical technologist should have: a gamma detection probe (sterile-draped), specimen containers WITHOUT formalin (the specimen goes FRESH for frozen section pathology to determine if axillary dissection is needed during the same procedure), and blue dye available on the sterile field. If the sentinel node is negative for metastasis, further axillary dissection is avoided, reducing morbidity.",
