    rationale: "Pneumatic tourniquet pressure should be individualized based on the patient's systolic blood pressure plus a safety margin. For upper extremity procedures, the standard is 50-75 mmHg above systolic blood pressure, typically not exceeding 250 mmHg. For lower extremity procedures, the standard is 100-150 mmHg above systolic, typically not exceeding 350 mmHg. Excessive pressure causes nerve and tissue damage (tourniquet paralysis). Maximum inflation time is generally 1 hour for the upper extremity and 1.5-2 hours for the lower extremity, with 15-20 minute deflation periods for reperfusion if extended use is needed. The limb is exsanguinated using an Esmarch bandage before inflation. The surgical technologist should document tourniquet application time, pressure, location, and total inflation time.",
