    rationale: "In pharmacology, a 1% solution means 1 gram of solute per 100 mL of solution, which equals 10 mg/mL. This is a critical calculation for surgical technologists who prepare local anesthetics on the sterile field. For lidocaine: the maximum dose without epinephrine is 4.5 mg/kg, and with epinephrine is 7 mg/kg. For a 70 kg adult, the maximum dose of 1% lidocaine with epinephrine is 490 mg, or 49 mL of solution. The surgical technologist must label all medications on the sterile field (drug name, concentration, date/time), announce medications when passing them, and calculate volumes accurately. Medication errors on the sterile field are a significant patient safety concern — the 1% vs 2% concentration distinction is critical for dosing.",
