    rationale: "The Satinsky clamp is a partial-occlusion vascular clamp (side-biting clamp) that allows the surgeon to clamp a portion of a vessel wall while maintaining blood flow through the remaining lumen. This is particularly useful for creating anastomoses, repairing vessel lacerations, or placing bypass grafts without completely interrupting blood flow. The curved jaws of the Satinsky clamp are atraumatic (with DeBakey-type serrations) to prevent intimal damage. The surgical technologist should distinguish between partial-occlusion clamps (Satinsky, Cooley) and complete-occlusion clamps (DeBakey aortic, Fogarty, bulldog). For CABG procedures, the Satinsky clamp is used on the aorta for proximal anastomosis of vein grafts.",
