    rationale: "The TEP (Totally Extraperitoneal) approach for laparoscopic inguinal hernia repair requires specific equipment: a balloon dissector (or space-creating device) to develop the preperitoneal space without entering the peritoneal cavity, a 0° or 30° laparoscope, specialized trocars for the extraperitoneal space, polypropylene or polyester mesh (sized to cover the entire myopectineal orifice — typically 15 x 10 cm or larger), and a fixation device (tacker/stapler or fibrin glue) to secure the mesh. The surgical technologist should also have standard laparoscopic instruments available and conversion instruments in case conversion to open (Lichtenstein) repair is needed. The TEP approach avoids the peritoneal cavity entirely, reducing the risk of bowel injury and adhesion formation.",
