    rationale: "The Spaulding Classification categorizes patient care items into three levels based on infection risk. Critical items contact sterile tissue or the vascular system and pose the highest risk of infection — they MUST be sterilized (scalpels, hemostats, implants, vascular catheters). Semi-critical items contact non-intact skin or mucous membranes and require high-level disinfection at minimum (laryngoscope blades, respiratory therapy equipment, endoscopes). Non-critical items contact only intact skin and require low-level disinfection (blood pressure cuffs, stethoscopes, bed rails). The surgical technologist must understand these classifications to ensure proper processing of instruments and equipment. All surgical instruments are critical items and must undergo sterilization by validated methods.",
