    rationale: "Laparoscopic sleeve gastrectomy involves excising approximately 75-80% of the stomach along the greater curvature using sequential firings of an endoscopic linear stapler (such as Endo GIA). The surgeon places a bougie (calibration tube, usually 36-40 French) along the lesser curvature to size the gastric sleeve, then fires the stapler sequentially from the antrum to the angle of His. Multiple stapler reloads are needed (typically 5-7 firings). The surgical technologist must have sufficient stapler reloads available (various heights: green, gold, blue depending on tissue thickness) and a liver retractor (Nathanson) to elevate the left hepatic lobe for exposure. Unlike Roux-en-Y gastric bypass, sleeve gastrectomy does not involve creating a jejunal anastomosis.",
    difficulty: 4,
    category: "Intraoperative Procedures",
