    rationale: "Circular staplers (EEA — End-to-End Anastomosis) must be tested before use by firing the empty stapler to ensure the cutting blade and staple formation mechanism function properly. The surgical technologist should select the correct stapler diameter (21mm, 25mm, 28mm, 29mm, 31mm, or 33mm) based on the lumen size of the bowel being anastomosed — the surgeon specifies the size. The detachable anvil is inserted into one end of the bowel (proximal or through a trocar transanally for low anterior resection), and the stapler body is inserted through the other end. When fired, the stapler simultaneously creates a double staple line and cuts between them, creating the anastomosis. The 'donuts' (circular tissue rings) must be inspected for completeness — incomplete donuts suggest the anastomosis may leak.",
