    rationale: "A Penrose drain is a flat, soft, flexible latex (or silicone) tube that provides passive drainage from a surgical wound by capillary action and gravity. It is an open drainage system — the external end is typically secured with a safety pin and covered with a gauze dressing. Penrose drains are commonly used in: appendectomy (for abscess drainage), neck surgery, and extremity abscess drainage. They come in various widths (1/4 inch to 1 inch). The surgical technologist should have the appropriate size Penrose drain available and a safety pin for securing it. In contrast, closed-suction drains (Jackson-Pratt, Hemovac, Blake) use negative pressure for active drainage and are preferred in many situations because they reduce the risk of ascending contamination. For patients with latex allergy, silicone Penrose drains must be used.",
