    rationale: "Oxidized regenerated cellulose (ORC/Surgicel) is an absorbable hemostatic agent that works by providing a physical matrix for clot formation and has a low pH that denatures blood proteins. Important safety considerations: Surgicel should NOT be used near nerves because it swells when absorbing blood and can cause nerve compression. It should NOT be left in closed spaces or tight compartments for the same reason. It should NOT be used with thrombin because the low pH of Surgicel inactivates thrombin. Surgicel should be applied DRY (not moistened with saline) — saline decreases its hemostatic effectiveness. It should be removed after hemostasis is achieved whenever possible. Surgicel is absorbed in 7-14 days and can appear as an abscess on postoperative imaging.",
