    rationale: "Breaking scrub refers to any action or event that causes a scrubbed (sterile) team member to become contaminated during a procedure. This requires the team member to remove their contaminated gown and gloves, perform a new surgical hand scrub (or hand rub with alcohol-based solution), and re-gown and re-glove before returning to the sterile field. Common causes of breaking scrub include: touching an unsterile surface, contamination from splash or splatter, torn gown or glove, leaving the sterile field (stepping away from the table), and contact with a non-scrubbed person. The surgical technologist should have additional sterile gowns and gloves available in the room for this contingency. If the surgical technologist needs to leave the room during a case, another scrubbed person must take over the sterile field.",
